segments.text: Did anybody meet you?
How did you find a place to spend the night that night and a place to live?
We had to go to Brian.
Okay.
We stayed in a building that was...
It's a pawn shop now.
It's on north... north of the...
See, the courthouse was built like this, and it was all open on that.
And then the main street was down here.
And the reason for the change, moving the stuff down the main street, was that the rent got too high around the courthouse.
And so there wasn't anything there, just some big old houses.
And one of them up there, up there, what was it, the 24th, it'd be about 23rd Street or something.
It was on that side.
There was a house that we stayed in until our furniture came.
The furniture was shipped by railroad.
Did you bring any toys or anything with you?
No.
No, there wasn't much room in that old car, except it was a big outfit.
It had plenty of room in it.
But I don't remember that one.
But it was so big and so long that we didn't own it very long.
About what speed could it drive?
Okay.
That's going to go up 50, 60 miles.
Oh, it would?
Really?
Oh, it was a powerful engine.
Did your dad have to work on it much?
No.
It was sold here in a fellow that had a... We traded it for a 21 Dodge because Mama could drive that.
With a pillow behind her.
Otherwise, she couldn't drive.
So that's the reason we got rid of her.
How did y'all find a place to live?
Oh, the place to live.
You mean on the campus?
Yes, sir.
They were all set out.
They were set out by the administration.
Okay.
Describe the house y'all ended up with.
one we ended up with was on the end of what's called Quality Road.
You know where that is?
It's a street that's straight south.
I'll have to get a map to show it.
It's the one that goes... By the President's house now?
Yeah.
Okay.
And so that that
building there was supposed to be for the entomology department when Dr. Bilsing was head of the entomology department.
What's his name?
Bilsing.
B-I-L-S-I-N-G. And the house we lived in is on Texas, on Bush Drive right now.
We'll have to look and see what the street number is.
It's the one that burned
On Texas Avenue a while back.
You mean on George Bush?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, on the corner.
Yeah, well, we lived in that house for...
When it was on the campus.
On the campus, right down there.
It's the last house on this side.
Your last house on this side was ours.
The next house was one that Walton's had, T.O.
Walton and his family had.
And then the next house was
supposed to be for the head of the Agricultural Experiment Station.
A fellow named Connor, I remember, was one of them that lived in that house.
And then the next house, up there on the corner, was Dean Bowman's house.
And across the street from there, next to the guy in the hall,
was Frapp's house.
Dr. Frapp's.
F-R-A-P-P?
No, not P, not double P. I think he was just playing.
F-R-A-P?
S. Huh?
S-A.
No, Frapp's.
Frapp's.
F-R-A-P-S. What did he teach?
He was a...
Chemists for the state of Texas.
And they had a building which is now pretty close to the biology building.
About how long did it take your furniture, your family's furniture, to get here after y'all got here?
Oh, probably a million.
Two or three weeks.
You could see it was all crated.
The only way you could ship it, we didn't have it.
And they had to get some wagons and horses, and they hauled it from the railroad tracks up there, right up there.
How big was the college station?
The railroad station for the college.
How big was it?
It exists over here.
It's that size?
It exists on 30.
You go over that way.
That's the old building.
Okay.
Somebody built a model of it up here.
Yes, sir.
Well, it looks like that.
It was about that size.
No, that one's small.
Okay.
It was bigger.
Look at the one on 30.
You can find out how big it was.
It was a huge thing.
There were two of them.
There was the SP and the INGN.
Right side by side.
And the two tracks came down there like that.
Then they went down their little ways and crossed like this.
Was there any feeling that one of those railroads was better than the other?
No, you had to use it.
You had to use both of them.
That's what I thought.
You had to get to certain lines.
Now the INGN came through Hearn and you could take that and you could wind up in Kansas City the next day.
Now the
Southern Pacific, they had a good train service, excellent, excellent.
In the morning, you got two trains going, one north and one south like this, stopped everywhere.
And then in the afternoon, they did the same thing.
Same thing.
And then later, they put that streamliner on.
Now that was in 28.
That was much later.
It stopped here.
But it was a through train.
It didn't stop at all the little towns.
No, you see it stopped here because of the federal law that established the college.
The moral act specified that the
That the train have to stop at any...
I did not know that.
You should go read the moral act.
Very good, very good.
1860-some.
Yeah, 1863.
Yeah.
Well, you can read that, and it'll tell you that the clause in there that you have to, the train has to stop and discharge passengers.
This is an editorial note to the typist.
Mention of the Morrill Act, M-O-R-R-I-L-L, causes me to offer this addition.

Once, after giving a freshman history lecture here on this campus about 30 years ago, a young man came up to me and introduced himself and told me that he was the great-great-grandson of Senator Morrill and that he was the first member of the family
to go to a land-grant college.
I presume he was telling me the truth.

I did check and find out that he was a descendant, but I thought how nice it is that the first descendant of the man who sponsored the Land-Grant Act, the first one that ever attended a land-grant college, came to Texas A&M.
End of note.
So you all moved in.
Describe the house and the neighborhood.
Well, they took, they had to go take those big old wagons and things.
They went down there and unloaded that boxcar.
And they brought it up there and it was all crated.
Did the college do that?
Yeah.
Okay.
See, Dr. Bilson was single.
So he lost his
He didn't, he lost the fact that he had to.
And another one that was, that that house had been lived in was Charles Friley.
And his wife died in that house.
His first wife.
And Charles Friley was the registrar.
He later went to Iowa State College.
About how many faculty houses were there on campus?
Oh, there's a whole, you know, everything.
Yeah, 50.
At least 50 or so, or more than that.
Describe the house y'all were in.
How big was it?
How many bedrooms?
You just had to go over there and look at it.
No, but... Oh, it had... Oh, it had a big old kitchen in the back end.
Bathroom, good bathroom.
And my mother...
brought in that great big old range, that cast iron range, and put it up in there.
See, we had heatwood wood.
We had cookwood wood.
The only other thing we had was some of the families had a kerosene stove.
Three or four burners had a kerosene stove until 1928.
And that's when we brought in the natural gas.
But you did have electricity, but nobody had electric heating then, of course.
No.
And y'all didn't use any coal to heat with or to cook with?
Some coal?
The college used coal.
And that was an argument with the natural gas people.
They tried to tie the
The colleagues drew a contract so that the people around here could get it.
In other words, then they opened it up, and we're going to give gas to everybody, see?
But the guy made a mistake.
The Lone Star Gas Company went in there and they gave their construction crews all the data on the part they built around there.
They didn't tell them not to do it.
And so what happened was, I was out there one day and
See, our house was on that side.
This was after College Park was built in 28.
And our house was built in 24.
I saw them over there, and they were laying that pipe for a while.
And then I walked out there one day, and here they were with torches cutting it up.
And I knew what they were trying to do.
So I called my father and said, they're cutting that.
pipe up trying to fill those ditches back then.
He came down there and he told that construction foreman, you're on private property, get off.
So then they had to go to negotiation.
But we did get it all right.
Now, when you all got here, you came in the summer when you moved?
About in August.
August.
And then school started for you as a first grader?
No.
What grade were you in?
I wasn't in any.
Oh, you were too young?
No, my birthday is October the 7th.
Okay.
Therefore, I didn't qualify to start school.
So what did you do that year?
I went to some sort of...
preschool.
I don't remember what it was.
Who were your family's first close friends?
With whom did you all make...
The Waltons.
Describe the Waltons, please.
They were a wonderful family.
Wonderful.
The oldest one was what's her name?
They had
The oldest girl, he married, he was an instructor.
I mean, he did some, you have to excuse me sometimes.
Oh, I understand.
Don't worry about that.
My memory, your memory is good.
Mine fails.
Just a minute.
Well, the oldest girl, she was much older than I was.
She died here just a short time ago.
And then they had a, oh, yeah, they had Turner.
Turner, oh, now I remember.
Turner Walton was the oldest son.
He was
going to school to be a doctor, which we did.
We did.
Turtle water.
And then this oldest girl, and then there was another girl, and then there was Teal.
Was he about your age?
Yeah.
We all played together.
All right.
Describe...
They were good.
Now...
I told you we were on this side of the street.
But wait just a minute.
Describe Mr. Walton.
I don't know.
What size man was he and what was his purpose?
He was a large man.
But his real quality was he was head of the extension service.
That's where the original job was.
But he was a man, when you asked him to talk, he didn't talk.
He'd get in front of a crowd and talk to them.
Was he pleasant to be with?
I never heard, never saw him.
When we were there, we got smallpox.
No, we didn't get smallpox.
We got chicken pox.
And we never got nipped there either.
Two that we missed.
But there were others.
And they quarantined it.
The doctor had quarantined it.
The doctor quarantined us.
So dad went to town and got him a place to stay.
We had a trolley.
You remember the trolley?
It ran down Old College?
Yeah, it was there.
It was there.
About how often did it run?
I don't know.
It ran at the end of the day or back in the morning.
I don't really know.
Remember what it cost to ride it?
I just know the man that propelled it.
That's all I knew.
He worked in it.
I think they just run in the morning and in the evening.
They just carry a bunch of people back and forth.
Did it get its electricity from above or on the ground?
Overhead.
Overhead.
And the E.E.
department would back them up?
And where did it go downtown, Brian?
Where in downtown was its turnaround?
Was it on Main Street or at the courthouse?
No.
Well, GTE or, you know, where it is.
And the building that the old Eagle was in?
Mm-hmm.
Directly across from the library in Bryant.
Okay.
That building is there, and I think that somebody else is taking it over.
But it ended up right there.
Right there.
In that side street.
Okay.
Between there and the E building.
Okay.
Or the end, whatever it is.
Mm-hmm.
The...
It went there, and it went clean out to, went out to Ursul, all the way out.
Okay.
You could ride it through out there, and they had a convent out there.
Out at Villa Maria.
Yeah.
It had a convent that was, had your, not nurses, your... Sisters.
Sisters, mm-hmm.
I took a...
Music out there.
All right, so the first year you're not going to school, what were your dad, as far as you recall, what were your dad's first assignments as a faculty member here?
Get that department running.
Was he the first one?
Did he start ag engineering?
No.
You see, again, I told you about the one in Mississippi.
Mm-hmm.
training, they did it right here.
It's right there.
Right on the side of this, where the ag building is now.
There was a huge building like this.
The ag engineering building opened into that, which is sitting right here.
There you go.
You're right here.
You can go down through there.
And when they built the agriculture building in 24, they tore that building down.
How many faculty members were there in Ag Engineering when your dad came?
He had one man.
I don't think his name was Ernest.
His name was Kearney.
His last name was
He was a Negro.
They had two other men.
That's all that was in the department.
He was supposed to teach ag engineering.
And so he was busy hustling men to work.
They had the appropriations for like the whole thing.
Now who was the Dean of Agriculture then?
Kyle, describe him.
We don't know much about him in terms of his personality.
Great man.
Describe him physically.
What color hair?
Was he gray then?
He was a young man.
His wife was...
She was gorgeous.
And she just took care of everything.
And when we got married, she sent word to my mother that she wanted to take me and Margaret to the Gilders.
And she bought the rings.
My, my.
My, how great.
Now, where did the Kyles live?
Did they live on campus?
Yeah.
You know, that thing circled around here to the, what's the, towards the railroad where Auburn had his tower.
It's on the north part of that circle.
Okay.
The first house was probably Dean Kyle's house.
The second house was Dr. Mostella's house.
And then on the corner would be Dr. Ellinger's house.
Ellinger?
Yeah.
What did he teach?
He was a college physician.
Oh, yes, yes, yes.
And the building they just tore down, that was the hospital.
Yes, yes.
Was it standing then?
It was standing then.
Okay.
And the trolley came in on the east side of that and stopped right there in that little old house.
or almost out in front of the lawn there.
And that's where that trolley stopped.
What about the, please share as much information as you can remember about the Bazells, because he was the president when you all got here.
Well, the only thing I was telling you, the only thing I knew about him was the time he got around the house.
Got what?
Drowned out.
Oh, describe that.
Well, Dr. Rizal, the only thing wrong with him was that he was a man who would take it on himself not to let his subordinates react, but he'd react.
You know.
And so, I don't know the...
See, he lived in that house right there.
The president's house.
The president's home, and it's faced this way.
Right next to... And there was a building right here, which was a dormitory.
It had...
It was masonry all the way on each side of it, on each side of that thing.
But the... All the...
steps were in the middle of it were cast iron.
The old cast iron, it was built all the way from the foundation to clear up, but it was cast iron.
And you didn't even have treads on it.
You had a tread on it, but you didn't.
So what the kids did, you had these GI cans.
They were about this tall.
They called them GI cans, and they were water, heavy as hell, and about that big around, about 34, 30 inches tall, I guess, something like that.
So that was a favorite trick for them for grinding their buddies out, because they'd get up on the roof,
carry that water up there on the roof, and you'd be walking up there, and then all of a sudden, the water comes.
I never did get around that.
One time, he just missed me.
That's all.
He threw it right straight at me, but I missed him.
But at that time, they decided they'd make a ruckus, these kids in the dormitory, and get the doctor over there.
But they took their GI cans and rolled them down that stairway out of cast iron.
You can imagine the racket that that had.
So he came over there.
He started up that stairs and got up there to the top.
And he was going to go inside and see if he could straighten things out.
About that time, those little boys took that can and turned it upside down over the parapet wall.
and drowned him out.
And he backed down, and he sat there.
He backed down, and I don't know whether he looked up or something like that, and then he tried it again.
And they had another can, and they had drowned him out a second time.
And he just sat there on the steps and cried.
Did he do anything to him?
Did he punish him?
No.
Now, I interviewed his daughter two years ago.
Do you remember her?
She was an astonishingly pretty girl and went for two years as a freshman and a sophomore here in the early 20s.
Yeah, they did.
She attended classes.
You see, there's another one, too.
Mrs. Marstella.
Mm-hmm.
The dean's wife of the vet school, Dr. Mostella, she got everything done and all the coursework done, but they wouldn't let her sign a certificate to ask for a diploma.
Do you remember any mistreatment of those few coeds?
How were they treated by the...
I never saw them.
I never saw very many of them.
I just knew them later as grown women or grown girls.
They were much older than I was.
This Bazell daughter who died two weeks ago at age 97.
She's
He's nine years older than I am.
She said it was marvelous to be a co-ed then, because she said it was a lot of fun to be with all those boys.
Oh, yeah.
I gave her a photo of a picnic out on the lawn in front of the president's house, and Bernard Sabisa is standing over at one side.
Do you remember Mr. Sabisa?
No.
No, he was gone when I got...
I don't know, Marjorie Duncan.
Duncan was head of the thing there.
And she was my age.
And I was a dried up shrimp.
When I went to Interdandium, I weighed 105 pounds.
And I couldn't expand my chest or anything.
Yeah, the old colonel had to pass an examination to even go in the first two years of it.
He was there and I don't know, I think I must have had some fevers, some rheumatic fevers years ago and it just, I've always been short of breath and so
He looked at me and put his tape around me and I couldn't do nothing.
And so he just, I saw him do this.
He just grabbed ahold of it like this.
